[{"short_id":"fenwh4","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/fenwh4","created_at":"2022-03-01T13:57:26.000-06:00","title":"What's the best and safest way to call Python code from Javascript/Typescript?","url":"","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eI have some Python code doing data-science stuff, and I want to call it from my Javascript (soon to be Typescript) web backend. I would like to get as close to compile-time typechecking on this as I can given that it‚Äôs two different languages and type systems. What are some approaches I could consider?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI‚Äôve thought about:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI could create a JSON schema, and then generate \u003ca href=\"https://pypi.org/project/jsonschema-typed-v2/\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003ePython\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"https://www.npmjs.com/package/json-schema-to-typescript\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003eTypescript\u003c/a\u003e types from that. I would use an HTTP endpoint to receive the requests. At runtime I would validate against the schema on both sides (Python for request parameters, JS for the response)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA similar approach with protobufs? But then it‚Äôs a lot more opaque than an HTTP endpoint that can be inspected (and tested) by a human?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e???\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/fenwh4/what_s_best_safest_way_call_python_code","submitter_user":{"username":"vosper","created_at":"2017-04-03T01:40:09.000-05:00","is_admin":false,"about":"Software engineer / team-lead, based in Canterbury, New Zealand","is_moderator":false,"karma":1638,"avatar_url":"/avatars/vosper-100.png","invited_by_user":"jonalmeida"},"tags":["ask","javascript","python"]},{"short_id":"uh7bhf","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/uh7bhf","created_at":"2022-03-01T13:17:23.000-06:00","title":"NixOS Community Surve